  "text": "volatile components are also released, and reach the olfactory mucosa through an opening, which is situated on the upper wall of the palate. This combination of sensations is what makes up \"flavor\" [CITATION_1] . To reproduce this effect, the sensor outputs were concatenated into a single matrix, with an approach called \"data fusion\", which combines the outputs of multiple instrumental sources, and which responds to different signature phenomena, increasing the probability of correct classification [CITATION_2] . Then, the exploration of data was performed with PCA (Figure 3) , using the merged data matrix as input. \"RF-heated\" samples overlap each other, and are positioned near the \"raw\" and \"pasteurized milk\" clouds, indicating that the different temperatures had the same weak effect on the milk's flavor, which is comparable among the three types of milk. On the other hand, UHT milk is far from the others, because of the thermal treatment leading to the formation of undesired volatile compounds from raw milk components, to the production of off-odors, and to the denaturation of serum proteins, which releases sulfhydryl groups [CITATION_3] . The colors exhibited from the different samples were used as variables to perform a second PCA (Figure 4 ). \"RF-heated\" samples overlap each other, and are positioned near the \"raw\" and \"pasteurized milk\" clouds, indicating that the different temperatures had the same weak effect on the milk's flavor, which is comparable among the three types of milk. On the other hand, UHT milk is far from the others, because of the thermal treatment leading to the formation of undesired volatile compounds from raw milk components, to the production of off-odors, and to the denaturation of serum proteins, which releases sulfhydryl groups [CITATION_4] . The colors exhibited from the different samples were used as variables to perform a second PCA (Figure 4 ). RF-heated milk is close to the \"raw\" samples, indicating a strong resemblance between the appearances of these two groups. On the other hand, pasteurized and UHT milks are far away, at the opposite sides of the scatter plot. Pasteurized milk is on the left, because of the high correlation with the colors (Figure 5 ). RF-heated milk is close to the \"raw\" samples, indicating a strong resemblance between the appearances of these two groups. On the other hand, pasteurized and UHT milks are far away, at the opposite sides of the scatter plot. Pasteurized milk is on the left, because of the high correlation with the colors (Figure 5 ). RF-heated milk is close to the \"raw\" samples, indicating a strong resemblance between the appearances of these two groups. On the other hand, pasteurized and UHT milks are far away, at the opposite sides of the scatter plot. Pasteurized milk is on the left, because of the high correlation with the colors (Figure 5 ).",
